00:04:10.710 --> 00:04:14.010
pack on my back, and
we started up,

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:15.980
and I started gasping.

00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:17.730
He said he didn't think I was
going to make it out of the

00:04:17.730 --> 00:04:20.540
parking lot, because I was
gasping so loudly, but he was

00:04:20.540 --> 00:04:23.850
very handsome, so
I persevered.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:26.765
And when the sun rose, I was in
the most beautiful place I

00:04:26.765 --> 00:04:30.810
had ever been, high above the
clouds, and I fell in love

00:04:30.810 --> 00:04:34.050
with him, and with mountain
climbing, and with chemistry,

00:04:34.050 --> 00:04:37.500
and kept doing mountain climbing
and chemistry until I

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.890
was a grad student
at UC Berkeley.

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:43.640
And I just passed my qualifying
exams, and wanted

00:04:43.640 --> 00:04:47.280
to go on an adventure, and one
of my lab partners said,

00:04:47.280 --> 00:04:50.160
there's an expedition to Denali
and I'm going to go.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:51.260
Do you want to go?

00:04:51.260 --> 00:04:54.170
And I said, great, when
I pass my qualifying

00:04:54.170 --> 00:04:55.970
exams I'll go to Denali.

00:04:55.970 --> 00:04:58.820
And I wrote for the information
and it said women

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:03.130
can go on a Denali trip at a
reduced price, as far as base

00:05:03.130 --> 00:05:05.360
camp, to help with
the cooking.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:08.760
So I called the guy who is
leading the trip and I said, I

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:10.600
want to go to Deanli, but
I want to climb it.

00:05:10.600 --> 00:05:12.830
And he said, women aren't
physically strong enough or

00:05:12.830 --> 00:05:15.950
emotionally stable enough to
climb mountains like Denali.

00:05:15.950 --> 00:05:21.520
And I said, I was climbing with
my friends from Reed in

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:24.670
Peru, and we climbed higher
than Denali in the Andes.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:26.820
And he said, were you
the only woman.

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:28.120
And I said, yeah.

00:05:28.120 --> 00:05:31.140
And he said, did you really do
your share of the leading.

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:34.150
And I said, no, I probably
didn't, but I thought I

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:35.050
participated.

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:38.140
And he said, you are probably
just carried up the mountain.

00:05:38.140 --> 00:05:41.540
So I realized as long as I
climbed with all guys, and in

00:05:41.540 --> 00:05:44.730
those days most of the climbers
were guys, people,

00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:48.650
and maybe even me, would
question had I done my share.

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:51.590
So I thought, I wonder if we
can organize an all women's

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:54.170
team to Deanli, and that was
a very revolutionary

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:56.050
idea back in 1970.

00:05:56.050 --> 00:06:00.590
So we organized the Denali
Damsels, and here we are on

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:01.150
the mountain.

00:06:01.150 --> 00:06:04.710
And nowadays, people carry their
loads on the low slopes

00:06:04.710 --> 00:06:07.760
on sleds where they pull them,
but we hadn't thought of that

00:06:07.760 --> 00:06:11.450
back then, and to climb Denali
you need about 200 pounds of

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:14.220
food and gear, 30
days of food.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:16.930
And so the reason people thought
women couldn't do it

00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:18.910
is because they thought
women couldn't carry--

00:06:18.910 --> 00:06:20.540
you saw that big pack
we're carrying--

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:23.720
but we could, and we headed
up the mountain.

00:06:23.720 --> 00:06:27.030
It was a beautiful place.

00:06:27.030 --> 00:06:29.040
We got up to our high camp.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:30.390
I was the deputy leader.

00:06:30.390 --> 00:06:32.280
I'd organize the trip.

00:06:32.280 --> 00:06:39.090
I was 25 at the time, but the
leader was a 50 year old woman

00:06:39.090 --> 00:06:42.270
who was one of Alaska's
leading climbers.

00:06:42.270 --> 00:06:45.540
But most of the peaks in Alaska
aren't very high, and

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:48.000
it turned out she had an
altitude problem, so she was

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.420
really strong up to about 14,000
feet, but she didn't do

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:55.060
very well above 14, and
Denali is 20,000.

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:57.630
So we're at the high camp
here at 17,000 feet.

00:06:57.630 --> 00:07:02.290
It's summit morning, she has a
headache, she hadn't actually

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:03.300
been carrying her load.

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:06.280
She'd been feeling really badly,
and I said, Grace,

00:07:06.280 --> 00:07:08.880
maybe you shouldn't try for
the summit when you have a

00:07:08.880 --> 00:07:10.630
migraine and you
feel terrible.

00:07:10.630 --> 00:07:14.070
But she was really determined,
and so we headed up.

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:16.485
She was going slowly, but
it was a gorgeous day.

00:07:20.380 --> 00:07:24.000
We reached the summit-- she's
the person slumped down to the

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:25.790
right of the flag.

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:29.040
She wasn't eating, drinking.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:30.420
We weren't so happy.

00:07:30.420 --> 00:07:32.850
We were very happy, because we
hadn't even know if women

00:07:32.850 --> 00:07:33.700
could climb Denali.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:36.680
Every step of the way it was
like, can we actually do this,

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:37.290
and we did it.

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:40.450
We were on the top, but we
saw thick clouds coming.

00:07:40.450 --> 00:07:44.570
We heard a big Arctic storm
was forecast, and she was

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:48.700
really ill, and so we sort of
supported her down a little

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:52.990
way below the summit, she
collapsed unconscious.

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:58.310
And I was now the expedition
leader at age 25, with six

00:07:58.310 --> 00:08:01.030
people, an Arctic storm coming
in, and a unconscious person

00:08:01.030 --> 00:08:02.910
near the summit of Denali.

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:05.090
So we put her in a sleeping
bag with a

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:06.900
pack frame as a structure.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:08.670
We wrapped a climbing
rope around.

00:08:08.670 --> 00:08:11.370
We kind of made a stretcher, and
we hauled and lowered her

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:12.080
down the mountain.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:15.100
And I think you can see the
place where the summit is, the

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:18.475
place where grace collapsed, and
then we hauled and lowered

00:08:18.475 --> 00:08:22.370
her down that slope to where
it says bivvy site.

00:08:22.370 --> 00:08:24.100
I can't quite see in the back.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:28.350
And then another woman and I
stayed up with her on the

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:31.320
bivvy site watching the clouds
massing, this big

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:32.520
storm coming in.

00:08:32.520 --> 00:08:35.710
It was getting dark, and I'll
always remember that moment,

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:38.860
thinking if the storm comes,
what do we do.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:40.334
Do we stay here?

00:08:40.334 --> 00:08:42.010
Do we leave her?

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:47.050
It was a horrible moment, and
then fortunately she got a

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:51.080
little bit better, and we were
able to get her down the

00:08:51.080 --> 00:08:54.410
mountain before the storm really
hit, and we're down now

00:08:54.410 --> 00:08:56.340
at 14,000 feet.

00:08:56.340 --> 00:08:59.600
You can see the amount of snow
on our snow shoes, and we were

00:08:59.600 --> 00:09:03.290
going out every three hours to
shovel the snow off the tent,

00:09:03.290 --> 00:09:05.580
but I was a different person.

00:09:05.580 --> 00:09:09.130
That happening gave me so
much more self esteem.

00:09:09.130 --> 00:09:11.510
If you read "Breaking Trail"
you'll see I had a really

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:14.010
tough childhood where I was
always said pretty negative

00:09:14.010 --> 00:09:17.720
messages, and really never felt
very good about myself,

00:09:17.720 --> 00:09:20.460
and I do remember a long time
ago though, sitting in that

00:09:20.460 --> 00:09:23.190
tent thinking, I'm not
such a bad person.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:24.710
I got Grace down alive.

00:09:24.710 --> 00:09:25.570
We climbed Denali.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:27.490
I'm actually OK.

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:31.990
And it really gave me a lot of
confidence to have had such a

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:35.450
challenge, and to be
able to have gotten

00:09:35.450 --> 00:09:36.690
her down the mountain.

00:09:36.690 --> 00:09:41.180
So by the time we flew out, I
felt like I'd gone from being

00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:44.040
a 25 year old girl from Chicago
who climbed some

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:47.310
mountains, to a woman who could
lead expeditions, and

00:09:47.310 --> 00:09:49.190
dream up impossible things.

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:51.560
So my next big adventure
happened when I was back at

00:09:51.560 --> 00:09:54.230
grad school, hard at work
not writing my thesis.

00:09:54.230 --> 00:09:55.835
Has anybody engaged in
such an activity?

00:09:59.210 --> 00:10:02.660
So I went to the movies, North
Side Theater if any of you

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:06.610
know it, Berkeley, and "The
Endless Summer" was playing.

00:10:06.610 --> 00:10:10.010
It was the Beach Boys going
around the world with big surf

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:13.730
boards looking for the perfect
wave, and I watched them and I

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:16.660
thought, when I got my PhD I
want to go around the world

00:10:16.660 --> 00:10:17.990
and find the perfect mountain.

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:23.000
So I told my adviser, who
thought this would not be good

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.050
for my career as a chemist,
and I said, don't worry.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:28.160
I was studying a molecule
called Transfer RNA.

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:31.660
I said, I'll make a flag that
says tRNA, and I'll fly it on

00:10:31.660 --> 00:10:32.340
all the summits.

00:10:32.340 --> 00:10:34.000
I'll think about my research.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.320
So we planed to climb
in Europe for

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:41.140
a summer, in Africa.

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:43.300
By going up and down across
the equator, we could have

00:10:43.300 --> 00:10:46.740
five climbing seasons in 15
months, so it was Europe,

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:50.280
Africa, Asia, Australia, New
Zealand, back to being a

00:10:50.280 --> 00:10:53.350
chemist for the rest of my
life, one adventure.

00:10:53.350 --> 00:10:55.990
So I'll go quickly.

00:10:55.990 --> 00:10:58.260
We missed Europe, because my
thesis was late, but we

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:01.050
started in Ethiopia where we
climbed, in the background,

00:11:01.050 --> 00:11:04.690
the highest peak Ras Dashen,
which is 15,000 feet.

00:11:04.690 --> 00:11:08.820
And then we went to these
mountains, the Rwenzori.

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:10.140
Would you believe you're
looking at

00:11:10.140 --> 00:11:12.900
Uganda and the Congo?

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:16.160
They're on the equator on the
Congo-Uganda border, and

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:17.510
they're the source
of the Nile.

00:11:17.510 --> 00:11:20.360
Ptolemy said a long time ago,
the Nile came from snowy

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:21.930
mountains on the equator.

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:24.440
And the weather is so bad there
that nobody hardly knew

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:28.730
they existed, and we actually
climbed about all the peaks in

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:29.830
the Rwenzori.

00:11:29.830 --> 00:11:34.090
Here I am on the summit at
17,000 feet on the equator,

00:11:34.090 --> 00:11:35.660
and you see my flag says tRNA.

00:11:35.660 --> 00:11:39.180
I was thinking about
my research.

00:11:39.180 --> 00:11:42.880
This is Mount Kenya, which is
about a five eight rock climb,

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:45.090
about 18,000 feet.

00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:46.460
Kilimanjaro--

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:49.450
I have now a unique slide that
I've only shown a few

00:11:49.450 --> 00:11:54.700
audiences, but I actually a
couple months ago gave the big

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:57.230
lecture for the American Alpine
Club dinner in New

00:11:57.230 --> 00:12:01.560
York, and at the lecture was a
guy I had met on Kilimanjaro

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:03.290
that I hadn't seen since
Kilimanjaro.

00:12:03.290 --> 00:12:08.020
This was 1972, and at that
time we said no money.

00:12:08.020 --> 00:12:10.510
We were poor students doing this
on no money, carrying our

00:12:10.510 --> 00:12:12.310
own packs up Kilimanjaro.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:15.440
He was part of a guided party,
and the day we climbed

00:12:15.440 --> 00:12:18.910
Kilimanjaro it was snowing, and
the guided parties went to

00:12:18.910 --> 00:12:22.000
the crater rim and turned back,
but we didn't have a

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.380
guide so we walked around the
crater rim to the real summit.

00:12:25.380 --> 00:12:27.060
Anybody climbed Kilimanjaro
here?

00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:29.840
Yeah, so right there's a couple
miles, I think, you

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:33.430
walk up high where you hit the
crater to the high point.

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:35.780
But anyway, when we were going
by, I don't know how this

00:12:35.780 --> 00:12:38.530
happened, but I said something
like, I think I'm going to sun

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:40.550
bathe in my bikini
on this summit.

00:12:40.550 --> 00:12:43.240
And he said, I'll give you
$10 for a picture.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:46.650
Well that was a lot of money
for us in those days, so I

00:12:46.650 --> 00:12:50.420
hadn't seen this guy since 1972,
but there he was at the

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:54.160
Alpine Club dinner, and I was
able to squirrel through all

00:12:54.160 --> 00:12:57.080
my slides quickly and add
my summit picture from

00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:58.330
Kilimanjaro.

00:13:02.910 --> 00:13:03.470
It was fast.

00:13:03.470 --> 00:13:05.840
It was cold.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:07.310
It was a very fast picture.

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:12.020
So he gave me the $10.

00:13:12.020 --> 00:13:16.410
It's not it's worth as
much as it was 1972.

00:13:16.410 --> 00:13:19.640
So we carried on to Mount
Damavand, which is the highest

00:13:19.640 --> 00:13:22.870
peak in Iran, and then
we went to Kashmir,

00:13:22.870 --> 00:13:23.940
so we were so lucky.

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:27.340
We went to all these places you
can't go to now, and we

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.110
joined up with the local
Kashmiri Mountaineering and

00:13:30.110 --> 00:13:32.860
Hiking Club, who knew about
all these mountains that

00:13:32.860 --> 00:13:34.950
they'd tried to climb but never
could, because they

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:37.230
didn't have the techniques
and the gear.

00:13:37.230 --> 00:13:39.130
And mostly the idea of getting
up at 3:00 in the

00:13:39.130 --> 00:13:40.160
morning when the--

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:43.030
they would get up at 8:00 and
make chapatis, and not get up

00:13:43.030 --> 00:13:43.950
the mountain.

00:13:43.950 --> 00:13:47.320
And we would get up at 3:00
and cook over our little

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:50.760
primus, and be up at the summit
when the sun rose.

00:13:50.760 --> 00:13:52.980
Anyway, so they told us about
all these mountains that had

00:13:52.980 --> 00:13:55.420
never been climbed, and then
we climbed them all.

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:57.870
So here I was at age
26 doing first

00:13:57.870 --> 00:13:59.050
ascents in the Himalayas.

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:03.560
It was a long way from Chicago,
and I wasn't that

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:07.510
good a technical climber, but
I was really determined.

00:14:07.510 --> 00:14:10.300
So when there was really deep
snow and everybody said, the

00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:14.360
snow is too deep, let's just
not bother, I would sort of

00:14:14.360 --> 00:14:17.500
break trail through the deep
snow to the face of the ice

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.220
cliff where the guys who
were the good ice

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:20.360
climbers would take over.

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:23.650
So my specialty was indeed
breaking trail, plodding

00:14:23.650 --> 00:14:27.430
through snow, and as you'll
hear, doing science policy is

00:14:27.430 --> 00:14:29.110
just like breaking trail.

00:14:29.110 --> 00:14:30.820
Does anyone do anything in your
work where you feel like

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:32.160
you're plodding through
deep snow?

00:14:36.330 --> 00:14:39.040
These were some peaks in Kashmir
we did not climb that

00:14:39.040 --> 00:14:41.950
were really hard, but we were
so lucky to be at all these

00:14:41.950 --> 00:14:44.200
places that we were practically
the first

00:14:44.200 --> 00:14:46.000
Westerners.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.030
Then we went to Afghanistan
and did an expedition, and

00:14:50.030 --> 00:14:52.800
again, I felt so privileged to
have this wonderful time in

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:55.930
Afghanistan at a very happy
time for that country.

00:14:55.930 --> 00:15:00.200
There was a king, it was
modernizing, and in fact,

00:15:00.200 --> 00:15:04.040
after September 11, I showed
this slide show about

00:15:04.040 --> 00:15:08.820
Afghanistan, which led to
founding the Society for

00:15:08.820 --> 00:15:11.700
Preservation of Afghan
Archaeology.

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:14.940
From having climbed there, have
been involved with things

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:16.820
around Afghanistan.

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:20.530
So here I am at 20,000 feet in
Afghanistan, thinking about my

00:15:20.530 --> 00:15:23.420
tRNA research, right.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:25.540
But this was a very
memorable day.

00:15:25.540 --> 00:15:27.940
At this point it was 1973.

00:15:27.940 --> 00:15:30.880
All the world's highest
mountains of 8,000 meters or

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:34.640
higher had been climbed by men,
but no woman had ever

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:37.870
climbed to 8,000 meters, and
we were climbing a mountain

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:42.560
that was 7,500, and there was
a Polish expedition there.

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:46.410
We're heading up to the summit,
and we met coming down

00:15:46.410 --> 00:15:49.510
Wanda Rutkiewicz, who went on to
become the world's leading

00:15:49.510 --> 00:15:50.300
moment mountaineer.

00:15:50.300 --> 00:15:53.410
She was the first woman to climb
K2, the third woman to

00:15:53.410 --> 00:15:54.660
climb Everest.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:57.900
But meanwhile, we were on Noshaq
and she had just come

00:15:57.900 --> 00:16:03.420
down from climbing, it's like
24, five, 7,500 meters, and I

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:06.630
was heading up, and she gave
me a big hug, and said, we

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:09.360
will climb Annapurna together,
all women.

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:12.400
And so that moment in
Afghanistan was where the idea

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:14.760
came to climb Annapurna.

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:20.560
Meanwhile, I did lots of other
expeditions, I got my PhD, I

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:26.090
post doc'ed at Stanford in
bio-chem, and alternated

00:16:26.090 --> 00:16:28.460
climbing expeditions,
research.

00:16:28.460 --> 00:16:32.330
I was studying intermediate in
protein folding, and I went on

00:16:32.330 --> 00:16:35.440
an expedition in India
that changed my life.

00:16:35.440 --> 00:16:39.430
And it was an easy mountain
called Trisul, but it was,

00:16:39.430 --> 00:16:42.040
again, high, over
7,000 meters.

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:47.350
It had been climbed back in
1890, very easy, and on it was

00:16:47.350 --> 00:16:50.360
Bruce Carson, who was at that
time America's leading young

00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:51.380
rock climber.

00:16:51.380 --> 00:16:54.900
He had pioneered climbing the
hardest faces in Yosemite

00:16:54.900 --> 00:16:56.210
without pitons.

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:59.540
People used to drive pitons
into the rock, now Bruce

00:16:59.540 --> 00:17:02.680
pioneered putting chalk stones
in that don't scar the rock,

00:17:02.680 --> 00:17:06.130
and he had led people like
Yvon Chouinard and Royal

00:17:06.130 --> 00:17:08.900
Robbins, if you know those
names, up the first grade

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:12.000
sixes ever done in the valley
without pitons.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.060
And so we were on this
easy mountain.

00:17:15.060 --> 00:17:15.930
I'm a slow walker.

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:18.470
He was ahead with some
of his friends.

00:17:18.470 --> 00:17:21.839
I got to the summit and
his friend said, we

00:17:21.839 --> 00:17:23.750
think Bruce is lost.

00:17:23.750 --> 00:17:25.260
I don't think I have
a pointer.

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:26.710
I don't have a pointer do i?

00:17:26.710 --> 00:17:27.619
We're going to imagine.

00:17:27.619 --> 00:17:30.960
So you see those footprints
on the left?

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:32.710
Do you know what a cornice is?

00:17:32.710 --> 00:17:36.280
A cornice is where the wind
blows, like you have a rocky

00:17:36.280 --> 00:17:40.550
place, and the wind blows, so
you can have snow over air.

00:17:40.550 --> 00:17:45.650
It's like a big wave of snow,
and so Bruce got to the top

00:17:45.650 --> 00:17:46.350
with his friends.

00:17:46.350 --> 00:17:48.900
He was very careful climber,
always roped, but he unroped.

00:17:48.900 --> 00:17:52.660
He thought that point that you
see there was a higher summit,

00:17:52.660 --> 00:17:55.360
and where his footprints are
on the left, he went out on

00:17:55.360 --> 00:17:59.010
the point, but he was on a
cornice and fell to his death.

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:04.570
And you can see, this is from
the other side, that big

00:18:04.570 --> 00:18:09.190
cornice on the top, and we had
no idea that there was a--

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:11.430
India was very secretive in
those days about maps.

00:18:11.430 --> 00:18:13.240
We had no real map.

00:18:13.240 --> 00:18:21.240
We didn't know there was a
face, and so Bruce was 23

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:23.840
having done all this, and
fell to his death.

00:18:23.840 --> 00:18:29.310
And I was really depressed, and
I came back to Stanford,

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:32.760
and I didn't really want to
study protein folding.

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:35.310
I wanted to do something
for the world, for the

00:18:35.310 --> 00:18:37.100
environment, because Bruce
had been an early

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:39.610
environmentalists, like he did
the first big cleanups in

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:41.860
Yosemite Valley, getting
rid of all the trash.

00:18:41.860 --> 00:18:48.550
He was very much, and so a guy
who had been on my PhD orals

00:18:48.550 --> 00:18:51.110
committee called Bruce Ames--

00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:53.635
anybody here ever heard
of Bruce Ames?

00:18:53.635 --> 00:18:55.690
If you're in biology, but he had
something called the Ames

00:18:55.690 --> 00:18:58.570
test, where you could take
a chemical, put it on a

00:18:58.570 --> 00:19:01.670
bacterial plate, if it changed
the bacteria it was likely to

00:19:01.670 --> 00:19:02.140
cause cancer.

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:04.860
It was a cancer screening
tool that was kind of

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:10.385
revolutionary, and so I went to
see him and I said, I don't

00:19:10.385 --> 00:19:11.580
want to do protein
folding anymore.

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:12.160
It's not important.

00:19:12.160 --> 00:19:14.000
It turns out protein folding
is really important, how

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.740
proteins fold, for
lots of things.

00:19:16.740 --> 00:19:20.140
But I want to do something
environmental, and he said,

00:19:20.140 --> 00:19:23.570
you know, I'm kind of worry
about this flame retardant in

00:19:23.570 --> 00:19:24.910
kid's pajamas.

00:19:24.910 --> 00:19:27.040
It looks like it's a carcinogen
to me, and it's

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:30.260
actually 10% of the weight of
all the kid's pajamas in the

00:19:30.260 --> 00:19:33.440
country, and I think it
gets inside the kids.

00:19:33.440 --> 00:19:34.470
Do want to study that?

00:19:34.470 --> 00:19:37.730
He said it's so practical,
even the undergraduates

00:19:37.730 --> 00:19:40.170
won't-- you know scientists like
to do theoretical things,

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:41.140
nothing too practical.

00:19:41.140 --> 00:19:42.080
He said, nobody will
look at it.

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:43.030
Would you look at it?

00:19:43.030 --> 00:19:44.190
I was sufficiently depressed.

00:19:44.190 --> 00:19:46.420
I said sure.

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:49.860
So I found a child who--

00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:51.940
and the chemical is called
brominated tris.

00:19:51.940 --> 00:19:54.465
All the pajamas pretty much
kids in America were

00:19:54.465 --> 00:19:55.850
wearing were 10%.

00:19:55.850 --> 00:19:59.270
I found a mom who'd bought her
children's pajamas in England,

00:19:59.270 --> 00:20:01.060
so they'd never worn
the tris pajamas.

00:20:01.060 --> 00:20:03.470
So we put a child in
the tris pajamas,

00:20:03.470 --> 00:20:04.650
collected their urine.

00:20:04.650 --> 00:20:07.240
The next morning there were tris
breakdown products in the

00:20:07.240 --> 00:20:10.860
child's urine, which meant the
tris was going from the

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:12.790
pajamas into the child.

00:20:12.790 --> 00:20:15.560
And then we ran a screen to see
if it was a mutagen, did

00:20:15.560 --> 00:20:17.720
it change DNA, and it was
one of the strongest

00:20:17.720 --> 00:20:20.190
mutagens we'd ever seen.

00:20:20.190 --> 00:20:23.540
And I thought, oh my goodness,
we have to write a paper.

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:25.320
We have to alert the
parents of America.

00:20:25.320 --> 00:20:26.870
This is a disaster.

00:20:26.870 --> 00:20:29.030
And then I got invited
to this mountain.

00:20:29.030 --> 00:20:31.860
Do you know what mountain
this is?

00:20:31.860 --> 00:20:33.350
Anybody know?

00:20:33.350 --> 00:20:35.550
Big mountain.

00:20:35.550 --> 00:20:40.232
Everest, Mount Everest, and at
that point, Everest had been

00:20:40.232 --> 00:20:41.710
climbed once by Americans.

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:45.570
1963, and this is the 50th
anniversary of the first

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:47.120
American ascent of Everest.

00:20:47.120 --> 00:20:49.560
And if anyone's interested, I'm
on the honorary committee

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:52.420
for the 50th anniversary party,
which is in Richmond,

00:20:52.420 --> 00:20:55.110
California in the
end of February.

00:20:55.110 --> 00:20:57.550
If anybody wants to go,
see me afterwards.

00:20:57.550 --> 00:20:58.440
I'll give you an invitation.

00:20:58.440 --> 00:21:01.740
So there's a 50th anniversary
party for Everest.

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:04.210
So Everest was climbed
by Americans in '63.

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:11.030
This was '76, the bicentennial
year, and no American woman

00:21:11.030 --> 00:21:14.500
had ever eve tried Everest,
and so I had

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:16.320
this terrible choice.

00:21:16.320 --> 00:21:19.280
Did I write the paper about the
cancer causing pajamas, or

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:21.460
did I climb Mount Everest.

00:21:21.460 --> 00:21:23.475
So how many of you would
climb Mount Everest?

00:21:26.710 --> 00:21:28.815
How many of you would write
the paper about the cancer

00:21:28.815 --> 00:21:31.610
causing pajamas?

00:21:31.610 --> 00:21:34.740
So I did both.

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:39.410
So here is our team, and we
climbed in beautiful places

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:43.290
like the Khumbu Icefall, rigged
ladders, but every

00:21:43.290 --> 00:21:45.160
night I would get to
camp and I would

00:21:45.160 --> 00:21:47.010
write more of my paper.

00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:51.500
And here we are in the great
Khum, and when I reached my

00:21:51.500 --> 00:21:53.810
high point, now my flag
says the mutants.

00:21:53.810 --> 00:21:56.490
That petri dish has no tris,
the one with only two

00:21:56.490 --> 00:21:59.010
colonies, and you can't see
blowing in the wind the one

00:21:59.010 --> 00:22:01.310
with lots of tris where there
are lots of mutations.

00:22:01.310 --> 00:22:02.550
But I'd finished my paper.

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:06.760
I sent it by mail runner back to
Berkeley, and we did reach

00:22:06.760 --> 00:22:11.970
the summit of Everest on October
15, 1976 for the

00:22:11.970 --> 00:22:15.880
bicentennial, and then the next
January our paper was

00:22:15.880 --> 00:22:17.540
published in "Science."

00:22:17.540 --> 00:22:21.380
And I always include the title
of this paper in my talks,

00:22:21.380 --> 00:22:26.250
because it really says what our
Institute is now doing.

00:22:26.250 --> 00:22:30.060
So the subtitle, which I can't
read back there, "The main

00:22:30.060 --> 00:22:33.680
flame retardant in children's
pajamas is a mutagen and

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:37.540
should not be used." For those
of you read scientific papers,

00:22:37.540 --> 00:22:40.360
is that an unusual title?

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:43.720
What do all scientific papers
recommend as the next

00:22:43.720 --> 00:22:45.900
steps at the end?

00:22:45.900 --> 00:22:48.800
More research, and that's
pretty much all they

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:53.480
recommend, and we went, oh my
god, every kid in the country

00:22:53.480 --> 00:22:57.530
is wearing toxic pajamas, and so
we really recommended that.

00:22:57.530 --> 00:23:02.890
We did media, and three months
after the paper came out, tris

00:23:02.890 --> 00:23:05.050
was banned from kid's pajamas.

00:23:05.050 --> 00:23:07.070
So some of you might have
been those kids.

00:23:07.070 --> 00:23:10.000
It was only used for a couple
years, '74 and '75, or maybe

00:23:10.000 --> 00:23:13.250
those were your parents who
didn't wear the tris pajamas

00:23:13.250 --> 00:23:14.450
for that long.

00:23:14.450 --> 00:23:18.050
And it made me realize that
it's really important for

00:23:18.050 --> 00:23:21.680
scientists to, at some point,
go from saying more research

00:23:21.680 --> 00:23:25.640
is needed, to taking a stand and
saying there is a problem

00:23:25.640 --> 00:23:28.100
here, and something needs to
be done about it, and so we

00:23:28.100 --> 00:23:30.500
now have the Green Science
Policy Institute.

00:23:30.500 --> 00:23:35.050
Our mission is to bring the best
science to change policy

00:23:35.050 --> 00:23:36.760
in the public interest.

00:23:36.760 --> 00:23:40.300
So brominated tris was banned,
and when something is banned,

00:23:40.300 --> 00:23:43.970
industry likes to keep things
as similar as possible.

00:23:43.970 --> 00:23:45.540
So what do you think
the replacement for

00:23:45.540 --> 00:23:48.130
brominated tris was?

00:23:48.130 --> 00:23:52.270
Chlorinated tris, and so we
ran mutagenicity tests.

00:23:52.270 --> 00:23:53.200
It also changed DNA.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:23:58.330
It was also banned from kid's
pajamas, but chlorinated tris

00:23:58.330 --> 00:24:03.230
turns out to be the number one
chemical in furniture, and

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:05.700
other baby products today.

00:24:05.700 --> 00:24:09.790
So anyone here have
a couch from Ikea?

00:24:09.790 --> 00:24:11.810
What year did you buy it?

00:24:11.810 --> 00:24:12.780
AUDIENCE: Just this year.

00:24:12.780 --> 00:24:13.430
ARLENE BLUM: Oh, this year.

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:15.490
Well, it's maybe not too bad.

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:16.700
What about yours?

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:17.970
AUDIENCE: Who knows.

00:24:17.970 --> 00:24:21.900
ARLENE BLUM: OK, so if you
bought your couch between 2005

00:24:21.900 --> 00:24:25.550
and 2011, it contains
chlorinated tris, all the Ikea

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:27.570
couches, and pretty much
all the couches.

00:24:31.790 --> 00:24:35.000
But basically anyone in
California who has a couch has

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:38.370
tris or a related chemical in
it, so it was banned from baby

00:24:38.370 --> 00:24:41.090
pajamas, but not
from furniture.

00:24:41.090 --> 00:24:42.650
But we didn't know
that back then.

00:24:42.650 --> 00:24:45.160
We though, yay, we've
solved the problem.

00:24:45.160 --> 00:24:47.830
And I thought, it's time to give
women a chance to climb

00:24:47.830 --> 00:24:49.180
an 8,000 meter peak.

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:51.310
I'd met Wanda in Afghanistan.

00:24:51.310 --> 00:24:52.950
She said, let's climb
Annapurna.

00:24:52.950 --> 00:24:54.350
It seemed like a
good mountain.

00:24:54.350 --> 00:24:57.070
It was the first 8,000 meter
peak ever climbed.

00:24:57.070 --> 00:25:00.280
On my way back from Everest
I got a permit for it.

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:08.250
We put together a team who
ranged in age from 20 to 50.

00:25:08.250 --> 00:25:09.580
Actually, there is Dan.

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:11.680
Irene is not here, is she?

00:25:11.680 --> 00:25:17.566
Dan's wife Irene was the first
woman to climb Annapurna.

00:25:17.566 --> 00:25:19.120
Sorry if I'm embarrassing
you, Dan.

00:25:21.920 --> 00:25:23.960
Anyway, so there's Irene and
the rest of our team.

00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:25.390
Thank you for coming again.

00:25:25.390 --> 00:25:27.580
I'm sure Dan has seen--

00:25:27.580 --> 00:25:31.300
the later part's different,
you'll see.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:32.560
So we're all still friends.

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:33.800
We have reunions.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:38.940
We had to raise $80,000 to fund
our expedition, and We

00:25:38.940 --> 00:25:41.890
raised it selling these
t-shirts, and if anyone wants

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:45.470
it, you just Google Annapurna
t-shirts, and you can get them

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:47.130
from our website.

00:25:47.130 --> 00:25:49.265
So I'll quickly go through--

00:25:49.265 --> 00:25:50.270
see how we're doing on time--

00:25:50.270 --> 00:25:52.620
some of the beautiful pictures
on Annapurna.

00:25:52.620 --> 00:25:54.810
It was one of the most gorgeous
places I've ever

00:25:54.810 --> 00:25:57.590
been, but one of the
most dangerous.

00:25:57.590 --> 00:26:00.400
We didn't know it then, but
Annapurna has the highest

00:26:00.400 --> 00:26:03.470
fatality rate of any of
the 8,000 meter peaks.

00:26:03.470 --> 00:26:05.370
It's really high precipitation,
so there are

00:26:05.370 --> 00:26:11.090
these huge avalanches, really
amazing steep slopes.

00:26:11.090 --> 00:26:13.740
It's considered the most
difficult and the most

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:15.640
dangerous of the 8,000
meter peaks.

00:26:15.640 --> 00:26:20.960
Not the best choice, but we
persevered, broke trail, and

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:21.970
reached the summit.

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:27.070
There's Irene in the center,
and two Sherpa teammates.

00:26:27.070 --> 00:26:28.570
Two of the women on
our team, two

00:26:28.570 --> 00:26:29.930
Sherpas reached the summit.

00:26:29.930 --> 00:26:33.800
We unfurled a Nepali flag,
American flag, women's place

00:26:33.800 --> 00:26:36.240
is on top flag, all
held together by a

00:26:36.240 --> 00:26:37.490
save the whales pin.

00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:44.820
Headed down there was a second
summit attempt, and the two

00:26:44.820 --> 00:26:48.220
women on that fell to their
deaths, so climbing mountains

00:26:48.220 --> 00:26:51.450
like this can be very,
very dangerous.

00:26:51.450 --> 00:26:53.700
So after Annapurna--

00:26:53.700 --> 00:26:56.260
there's Irene in front
of Annapurna--

00:26:56.260 --> 00:27:00.290
I wanted to do an expedition
to a safe, quote, "easier"

00:27:00.290 --> 00:27:05.870
mountain, and we did a hard
first ascent in India with an

00:27:05.870 --> 00:27:08.000
Indian American women's team.

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.240
We're congratulated
by Indira Gandhi.

00:27:10.240 --> 00:27:13.150
I said I'd always dreamed of
walking the whole length of

00:27:13.150 --> 00:27:14.400
the Himalayan Mountain range.

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:16.620
It's a thing, once you get a
dream or a vision in your

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:18.550
mind, you kind of have
to make it happen.

00:27:18.550 --> 00:27:21.540
So I thought, walk across the
Himalayas, but the borders

00:27:21.540 --> 00:27:24.890
were closed to Westerners, but
Mrs. Gandhi said she thought

00:27:24.890 --> 00:27:29.200
she could help, and we got
permission, and we started in

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:35.510
Bhutan and walked all the way
across Bhutan, India, Nepal.

00:27:35.510 --> 00:27:38.310
I turn out to not have a very
good sense of direction, but

00:27:38.310 --> 00:27:40.420
Hugh Swift, who I was walking
with, had just finished

00:27:40.420 --> 00:27:43.270
writing a guidebook, so he knew
how to find the way, and

00:27:43.270 --> 00:27:45.400
I was pretty good
at the politics.

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:50.480
And so we crossed 19,000 foot
passes, and drop down, down,

00:27:50.480 --> 00:27:52.240
down terraced valleys.

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:54.990
Everywhere we came it seemed
like a very auspicious day.

00:27:54.990 --> 00:27:59.180
This was the annual archery
festival in Bhutan.

00:27:59.180 --> 00:28:01.370
Most places, almost the whole
time we were in places, there

00:28:01.370 --> 00:28:04.150
had never been a Westerner
before, so we were greeted

00:28:04.150 --> 00:28:07.860
like visitors from the gods
by the local people.

00:28:07.860 --> 00:28:10.970
The one day we were in
[INAUDIBLE], the Dalai Lama

00:28:10.970 --> 00:28:14.540
was there giving a
talk in English.

00:28:14.540 --> 00:28:17.340
Yeah, it was like auspicious
day all the way.

00:28:17.340 --> 00:28:19.420
Every day was an
auspicious day.

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:22.790
We entered Nepal on the Day of
the Dog when dogs were given

00:28:22.790 --> 00:28:24.280
little marigold wreaths,
and little

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:27.420
tikas and special treats.

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:31.225
We funded out trip by having
trekking groups that met us,

00:28:31.225 --> 00:28:34.460
and brought us supplies, and
walked with us for a few days.

00:28:34.460 --> 00:28:38.880
And I still lead treks, one or
two a year, and indeed we have

00:28:38.880 --> 00:28:40.010
sign up sheets.

00:28:40.010 --> 00:28:42.570
This is a cue to pass
out sign up sheets.

00:28:42.570 --> 00:28:45.080
If anybody wants to be on our
mailing list, we'll pass out

00:28:45.080 --> 00:28:48.580
sign up sheets, and basically
you'll hear for

00:28:48.580 --> 00:28:50.480
me if we have trips.

00:28:50.480 --> 00:28:52.095
I think I'm doing a trip--

00:28:55.190 --> 00:28:57.765
now there's a scientific meeting
in Switzerland, so

00:28:57.765 --> 00:29:01.880
then I'm going to do a trip
from Charmonix to near the

00:29:01.880 --> 00:29:04.110
Matterhorn, along the Haute
Route in August.

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:06.470
So I do one or two
trips a year.

00:29:06.470 --> 00:29:07.560
We're really lucky last year.

00:29:07.560 --> 00:29:10.790
We did a great trek in Burma
right when it opened, so

00:29:10.790 --> 00:29:12.440
starting from this--

00:29:12.440 --> 00:29:14.960
and then you actually get to
hear a lot about flame

00:29:14.960 --> 00:29:17.900
retardants if you sign the list,
so if you don't want to

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:21.970
hear about flame retardants,
write adventures only.

00:29:21.970 --> 00:29:24.850
So we send out flame retardant
messages once a month, and

00:29:24.850 --> 00:29:28.710
adventure messages about
four times a year.

00:29:28.710 --> 00:29:32.400
So we took pictures of the
beautiful women who lived in

00:29:32.400 --> 00:29:38.230
the Himalayas as we walked
across, who did a lot of work.

00:29:38.230 --> 00:29:43.930
And namaste, the greeting, I
respect the spirit in you.

00:29:43.930 --> 00:29:47.310
From that trip, I came back and
wanted to share all these

00:29:47.310 --> 00:29:49.860
auspicious days in the Himalayas
with my friends back

00:29:49.860 --> 00:29:50.990
in Berkeley.

00:29:50.990 --> 00:29:52.650
We started to Berkeley
Himalayan Fair.

00:29:52.650 --> 00:29:56.585
Has anybody here been to
the Himalayan Fair?

00:29:56.585 --> 00:29:58.510
Sorry, I can't read the dates.

00:29:58.510 --> 00:30:00.440
I'll turn around.

00:30:00.440 --> 00:30:03.690
Yeah, so next May 18th and 19th,
if you want to come to

00:30:03.690 --> 00:30:07.490
Berkeley Live Oak Park, we'll
have a big Himalayan party,

00:30:07.490 --> 00:30:10.410
food, dancing, and all the
Himalayan people from the West

00:30:10.410 --> 00:30:10.940
coast come.

00:30:10.940 --> 00:30:12.850
It's a great match-making
thing.

00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:15.180
Nepali people in different
cities, they all come and they

00:30:15.180 --> 00:30:16.875
meet their husbands and
wives and things at

00:30:16.875 --> 00:30:19.160
the Himalayan Fair.

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:21.800
And I have the best booth
since I founded it.

00:30:21.800 --> 00:30:22.420
Come say hi.

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:25.180
I'm under the big tree right
across from the stage.

00:30:25.180 --> 00:30:28.230
Everyone's invited to hang
out at my booth.

00:30:28.230 --> 00:30:31.040
So my most recent adventures
were with my daughter

00:30:31.040 --> 00:30:34.460
Annalise, and I rightfully
figured she might not like

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:38.040
walking, so when she was a baby,
her dad and I decided

00:30:38.040 --> 00:30:40.370
we'd have a last big adventure,
and we carried her

00:30:40.370 --> 00:30:45.140
across the Alps from Yugoslavia
to France in her

00:30:45.140 --> 00:30:46.755
cute, Gor-Tex baby suit.

00:30:50.320 --> 00:30:54.120
Anyway, and then here's Annalist
on her gap year

00:30:54.120 --> 00:30:55.660
teaching English in Guatemala.

00:30:55.660 --> 00:30:59.010
Annalise, she's an environmental
engineer.

00:30:59.010 --> 00:31:00.560
She doesn't like hiking
and camping.

00:31:00.560 --> 00:31:04.240
She complains bitterly about
sleeping on the ground, but

00:31:04.240 --> 00:31:07.000
she's an environmental engineer
who studies water and

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:08.970
sanitation in developing
countries, so

00:31:08.970 --> 00:31:10.160
I'm proud of her.

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:12.290
She cares about the world.

00:31:12.290 --> 00:31:14.600
And meanwhile, I wrote
two books.

00:31:14.600 --> 00:31:17.720
"Annapurna," which took
about a year to write.

00:31:17.720 --> 00:31:19.260
Anybody here read "Annapurna?"
Some of you.

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:20.840
A few people, yeah.

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:23.400
And then after that I thought,
well I'll spend another year

00:31:23.400 --> 00:31:27.620
and write a book about how I
came to Annapurna, and wrote

00:31:27.620 --> 00:31:33.430
"Breaking Trail," which tells a
lot of stories, and it ended

00:31:33.430 --> 00:31:36.190
right before my daughter
started college.

00:31:36.190 --> 00:31:38.900
It took me 20 years to write
"Breaking Trail"-- not an easy

00:31:38.900 --> 00:31:41.860
book-- about my childhood,
and it was a tough book.

00:31:41.860 --> 00:31:45.040
But I wrote it, and then I
actually hadn't done science

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:46.350
for 26 years.

00:31:46.350 --> 00:31:47.140
I'd been a mom.

00:31:47.140 --> 00:31:50.220
I'd done leadership training
here in Silicon Valley, and I

00:31:50.220 --> 00:31:52.360
thought, I want to go back to
science, but I really don't

00:31:52.360 --> 00:31:53.570
know anything.

00:31:53.570 --> 00:31:56.300
And that was six years ago, and
this six years have been

00:31:56.300 --> 00:31:59.180
the biggest adventure of my
life, much harder than

00:31:59.180 --> 00:32:02.190
climbing Annapurna, and
way more important.

00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:05.070
And the problem--

00:32:05.070 --> 00:32:06.360
before I do that,
maybe just ask.

00:32:06.360 --> 00:32:09.360
How many people here think if
a product is in your shampoo

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:12.180
or your toothpaste, someone's
making sure it's

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:13.430
safe for your health?

00:32:16.890 --> 00:32:20.310
OK, and how many people think
there can be cancer-causing,

00:32:20.310 --> 00:32:23.560
harmful chemicals in an everyday
product, and the EPA

00:32:23.560 --> 00:32:25.580
knows about it and are powerless
to do anything?

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:35.850
And unfortunately, the second is
true, and the reason is we

00:32:35.850 --> 00:32:37.840
only have one law--

00:32:37.840 --> 00:32:41.310
so in America, foods, drugs, and
pesticides are regulated.

00:32:41.310 --> 00:32:44.180
All other chemicals are
regulated by something called

00:32:44.180 --> 00:32:53.030
the Toxic Substances Control
Act of 1976, and when that

00:32:53.030 --> 00:32:56.880
passed, it wasn't a very good
law, and it has no authority.

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:00.570
So asbestos, which kills
thousands of people every

00:33:00.570 --> 00:33:03.260
year, the EPA tried and tried
and cannot regulate.

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:06.370
So chemicals can be really
harmful, the EPA can know, and

00:33:06.370 --> 00:33:08.330
they can be in your
toothpaste.

00:33:08.330 --> 00:33:10.480
And indeed, if anyone
uses Colgate Total.

00:33:10.480 --> 00:33:13.650
Anybody use Colgate Total
toothpaste here?

00:33:13.650 --> 00:33:14.530
My daughter did.

00:33:14.530 --> 00:33:18.310
It has triclosan in
it, which is a

00:33:18.310 --> 00:33:19.720
potentially harmful chemical.

00:33:19.720 --> 00:33:20.970
It's banned at Kaiser.

00:33:25.530 --> 00:33:27.670
There are really only a handful
of these real horror

00:33:27.670 --> 00:33:31.410
stories, and we can learn
these horror stories and

00:33:31.410 --> 00:33:34.790
protect ourselves, so don't
get too depressed.

00:33:34.790 --> 00:33:36.810
There really aren't tens
of thousands of evil

00:33:36.810 --> 00:33:37.630
chemicals out there.

00:33:37.630 --> 00:33:41.070
There's a small number, and we
can say what they are, and we

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:42.155
can be healthier.

00:33:42.155 --> 00:33:46.530
But the EPA has no authority
basically to regulate.

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:49.860
When they passed the Toxic
Substances Control Act, all

00:33:49.860 --> 00:33:53.400
the chemicals then were
grandfathered as being OK, and

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:56.060
with new chemicals they have
no authority to require

00:33:56.060 --> 00:33:59.350
information, so there's
no information on

00:33:59.350 --> 00:34:02.120
most of the new chemicals.

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:05.790
So the thing that I have
been working on, and

00:34:05.790 --> 00:34:07.560
I've come to realize--

00:34:07.560 --> 00:34:09.710
maybe you've heard that I work
on flame retardants--

00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:12.520
but I've come to realize the
problem really isn't flame

00:34:12.520 --> 00:34:13.449
retardants.

00:34:13.449 --> 00:34:15.710
And flame retardants are
chemicals that are used at

00:34:15.710 --> 00:34:19.350
really high levels, like 5% of
the foam in your couch is a

00:34:19.350 --> 00:34:21.290
flame retardant.

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:23.760
But the problem is flammability
standards, and

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:27.639
back in the '70s, several
flammability standards were

00:34:27.639 --> 00:34:32.239
passed where no on really
thought about do they provide

00:34:32.239 --> 00:34:35.030
a fire safety benefit, and
is there a harm from the

00:34:35.030 --> 00:34:36.620
chemicals that are used
to meet them.

00:34:40.050 --> 00:34:42.310
And the chemicals are
very profitable.

00:34:42.310 --> 00:34:45.449
The companies that make them do
a lot of lobbying to make

00:34:45.449 --> 00:34:48.420
new laws that require more of
the use of their chemicals.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:51.969
And this is a very major health
problem, but a solvable

00:34:51.969 --> 00:34:54.770
health problem, and we're going
to talk about in the

00:34:54.770 --> 00:34:57.920
'70s, there was a furniture
flammability standard passed

00:34:57.920 --> 00:35:01.000
called Technical Bulletin 117.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:04.870
There was a code for foam
plastic insulations in

00:35:04.870 --> 00:35:08.590
buildings passed with something
called the Steiner

00:35:08.590 --> 00:35:13.190
Tunnel Test, and their
flammability standards for

00:35:13.190 --> 00:35:16.270
electronics, and we're going
to say the most about

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.200
Technical Bulletin 117.

00:35:18.200 --> 00:35:21.450
If you go home and look at your
couch, they're all going

00:35:21.450 --> 00:35:24.260
to have a sign saying
it meets TB117.

00:35:24.260 --> 00:35:27.810
That means the foam inside won't
burn for 12 seconds with

00:35:27.810 --> 00:35:32.160
a small flame, but the reality
is if you drop a candle on

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:33.900
your couch, the fabric
burns first.

00:35:33.900 --> 00:35:37.080
You have a large flame, the foam
burns, and there's really

00:35:37.080 --> 00:35:38.770
not much benefit.

00:35:38.770 --> 00:35:43.790
The chemical used to protect all
the furniture uses a flame

00:35:43.790 --> 00:35:48.820
retardant until it was banned
globally in 2005.

00:35:48.820 --> 00:35:53.830
In that picture of chemicals,
the top one is PCBs, which are

00:35:53.830 --> 00:35:55.820
carcinogens and harmful.

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:58.960
The center one is that flame
retardant, and then the bottom

00:35:58.960 --> 00:36:02.090
ones are dioxins and furans,
which are really harmful, so

00:36:02.090 --> 00:36:03.940
it's a chemical that's
halfway in structure

00:36:03.940 --> 00:36:06.300
between a PCB and a dioxin.

00:36:06.300 --> 00:36:08.850
When I asked a chemist what do
you think about students at

00:36:08.850 --> 00:36:10.960
Berkeley being exposed
to this chemical?

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:14.310
He said, only in a fume hood
with full protective gear.

00:36:14.310 --> 00:36:16.160
But that's what's in your
furniture if you have

00:36:16.160 --> 00:36:19.090
furniture from before 2005.

00:36:19.090 --> 00:36:21.450
So why is this important?

00:36:21.450 --> 00:36:24.640
We're exposed to these flame
retardants in our homes, in

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:28.930
our office place, in cars, and
they're slowly making their

00:36:28.930 --> 00:36:30.040
way into the food chain.

00:36:30.040 --> 00:36:34.410
Right now, about 90% of the
exposure is in our homes.

00:36:34.410 --> 00:36:38.170
If you look at levels in dust,
on the left you have outside

00:36:38.170 --> 00:36:41.270
the US very low levels, other
states in the middle.

00:36:41.270 --> 00:36:45.290
California has the highest
levels, because we, uniquely,

00:36:45.290 --> 00:36:46.890
have a furniture flammability
standard.

00:36:46.890 --> 00:36:49.960
No other state has a standard.

00:36:49.960 --> 00:36:53.610
Sadly enough, toddlers have
three times the level in their

00:36:53.610 --> 00:36:57.020
bodies compared to adults,
because they get their mothers

00:36:57.020 --> 00:36:58.470
level through the placenta.

00:36:58.470 --> 00:37:01.690
The chemicals are lipophilic,
fat loving, so they go into

00:37:01.690 --> 00:37:04.980
breast milk, and then toddlers
crawl in the dust and put

00:37:04.980 --> 00:37:08.320
their hands in their mouths.

00:37:08.320 --> 00:37:12.060
So a woman who has a higher
level of this flame

00:37:12.060 --> 00:37:14.130
retardant-- this is the one
that was banned, but is in

00:37:14.130 --> 00:37:15.360
older furniture--

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:18.850
it takes longer for her to get
pregnant, and then there are a

00:37:18.850 --> 00:37:21.010
number of neurological
impairments.

00:37:21.010 --> 00:37:22.180
And these are actually

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:24.700
epidemiology studies in people.

00:37:24.700 --> 00:37:29.730
There's maybe 20 or 30 studies
showing harm in people, and

00:37:29.730 --> 00:37:33.310
then this is the number
of studies in animals.

00:37:33.310 --> 00:37:34.470
This is well studied.

00:37:34.470 --> 00:37:36.710
There's an industry of
scientists around the world

00:37:36.710 --> 00:37:39.100
studying these flame retardants,
but yet this

00:37:39.100 --> 00:37:42.010
information never reaches
decision makers.

00:37:42.010 --> 00:37:44.610
So there's this many peer
reviewed papers, and if you go

00:37:44.610 --> 00:37:47.150
to a typical hearing in
Sacramento, you will hear from

00:37:47.150 --> 00:37:50.240
the chemical industry there is
no valid science showing any

00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:51.950
harm for many flame retardant.

00:37:51.950 --> 00:37:55.350
So this is a huge disconnect
that we're trying to bridge

00:37:55.350 --> 00:37:58.710
and can bridge, bringing good
science to decision makers.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:01.760
So to give you an example of
what happens, remember back

00:38:01.760 --> 00:38:04.880
with the children's sleepwear,
we had brominated

00:38:04.880 --> 00:38:06.410
tris, it got banned.

00:38:06.410 --> 00:38:10.760
We got chlorinated tris,
it got banned.

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:14.030
In our furniture, we had
[? penta ?], it got banned.

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:19.050
Then we got chlorinated tris,
and it is on the way out.

00:38:19.050 --> 00:38:22.790
Chlorinated tris been listed
as cancer causing, and we

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:25.840
stopped making it in the US.

00:38:25.840 --> 00:38:29.690
Most of the furniture from 2005
till now has chlorinated

00:38:29.690 --> 00:38:33.480
tris, and the replacement is
something called Firemaster.

00:38:33.480 --> 00:38:37.870
The manufacturers will not give
out samples to study, but

00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:40.710
colleagues of mine got one
sample, and it looks like it

00:38:40.710 --> 00:38:48.640
causes obesity and anxiety, so
it's an obesogen, so this is

00:38:48.640 --> 00:38:51.740
the newest flame retardant.

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:57.630
So I got my dust tested.

00:38:57.630 --> 00:39:01.200
I had some of the highest levels
in the world, very high

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:03.880
levels of this toxic flame
retardant, 97 parts per

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:05.410
million in my dust.

00:39:05.410 --> 00:39:07.330
So I got rid of my couch.

00:39:07.330 --> 00:39:10.900
That's my couch going into the
dumpster, and then three years

00:39:10.900 --> 00:39:13.490
later my level was down to
three parts per million.

00:39:13.490 --> 00:39:16.850
So getting rid of toxic
furniture works, but where

00:39:16.850 --> 00:39:17.840
does the couch go.

00:39:17.840 --> 00:39:21.580
Into a landfill where it can
leech out into wildlife, and

00:39:21.580 --> 00:39:23.170
all these top of the food chain

00:39:23.170 --> 00:39:25.390
carnivores have high levels.

00:39:25.390 --> 00:39:28.240
So is there a fire safety
benefit, and the

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:29.620
answer is not much.

00:39:29.620 --> 00:39:32.810
If you compare the blue, the
furniture without flame

00:39:32.810 --> 00:39:35.790
retardants, to the red, with,
you can see there's a few

00:39:35.790 --> 00:39:39.880
seconds delay in ignition,
three seconds longer, but

00:39:39.880 --> 00:39:43.720
twice as much smoke, five times
as much carbon monoxide,

00:39:43.720 --> 00:39:46.770
and 80 times as much soot.

00:39:46.770 --> 00:39:49.870
So that means you delay your
fire three seconds, but you

00:39:49.870 --> 00:39:52.636
get lots more of the smoke
and toxic gases.

