00:51:48.750 --> 00:51:51.790
profitable, but I think that
that can be solved.

00:52:01.730 --> 00:52:02.740
AUDIENCE: I have a
tiny question.

00:52:02.740 --> 00:52:06.660
I think I saw one of these
notices on a backpacking tent.

00:52:06.660 --> 00:52:09.100
Are they also treated with
flame retardants?

00:52:09.100 --> 00:52:11.760
ARLENE BLUM: They are,
unfortunately.

00:52:11.760 --> 00:52:14.540
And again, that might be a
time you might want flame

00:52:14.540 --> 00:52:19.280
retardants, and there are ones
that are safer, and there are

00:52:19.280 --> 00:52:23.440
ones that are less safe, and
it's a problem that because

00:52:23.440 --> 00:52:24.690
the EPA can't regulate.

00:52:28.160 --> 00:52:30.720
One of the projects we haven't
done is to just give the

00:52:30.720 --> 00:52:33.450
outdoor industry a list of what
they really harmful flame

00:52:33.450 --> 00:52:36.900
retardants are, and maybe they
could move from the harmful

00:52:36.900 --> 00:52:39.780
ones to the less harmful ones.

00:52:39.780 --> 00:52:41.900
And maybe they're already doing
that, I haven't looked

00:52:41.900 --> 00:52:45.720
into it, but lots of industries
are trying to move

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:48.790
from more harmful to less
harmful flame retardants and

00:52:48.790 --> 00:52:50.590
other chemicals.

00:52:50.590 --> 00:52:53.900
And I'm sure at Google when
you're doing your products,

00:52:53.900 --> 00:52:55.460
you're trying to move--

00:52:55.460 --> 00:52:58.660
there's something called the
green screen, where you can

00:52:58.660 --> 00:53:00.180
compare chemicals.

00:53:00.180 --> 00:53:03.320
So for backpacking tents you
might want flame retardants,

00:53:03.320 --> 00:53:06.730
maybe your stove's going to
explode, but you want to try

00:53:06.730 --> 00:53:09.610
to have the safest possible
flame retardants, or use

00:53:09.610 --> 00:53:12.770
materials that are inherently
fire resistant.

00:53:12.770 --> 00:53:15.370
So there are lots of ways you
can solve the flammability

00:53:15.370 --> 00:53:17.050
problem without putting
lots of toxic

00:53:17.050 --> 00:53:18.300
chemicals into things.

00:53:21.210 --> 00:53:25.460
AUDIENCE: In terms of affecting
policy decisions,

00:53:25.460 --> 00:53:28.830
what's the step between
publishing the paper and

00:53:28.830 --> 00:53:31.470
actually talking to the people
that are making the decisions?

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:34.330
ARLENE BLUM: That's a great
question, because in this

00:53:34.330 --> 00:53:38.910
field of flame retardants, I go
to meetings with hundreds

00:53:38.910 --> 00:53:43.210
of scientists who do paper after
paper about the harm and

00:53:43.210 --> 00:53:46.800
how their accumulating in
everything in the environment,

00:53:46.800 --> 00:53:51.820
and I'm like, write a
"Scientific American" article,

00:53:51.820 --> 00:53:52.400
do something.

00:53:52.400 --> 00:53:54.355
And they're like, well it's on
our website, or they can read

00:53:54.355 --> 00:53:55.640
it in the journals.

00:53:55.640 --> 00:53:58.400
But scientists have to realize
people aren't going to read it

00:53:58.400 --> 00:54:00.470
in the journals, and they're
not going to go to your

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:05.030
website, and scientists have
to take the trouble to put

00:54:05.030 --> 00:54:08.560
their science in a form
that's accessible.

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:12.430
I've been working with
epidemiologists who do studies

00:54:12.430 --> 00:54:17.950
showing harm in humans, which
is big news, and if they can

00:54:17.950 --> 00:54:22.010
effectively tell the press, at
least people can find out.

00:54:22.010 --> 00:54:25.340
So I think not all scientists,
but a small number of

00:54:25.340 --> 00:54:28.420
scientist, if they could make
that part of their mission,

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:30.350
and that's what we're
trying to do.

00:54:30.350 --> 00:54:32.850
There are some scientists who
care about this, and we're

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:37.430
helping do some communications
courses, facilitating

00:54:37.430 --> 00:54:40.400
scientist talking to decision
makers, because scientists

00:54:40.400 --> 00:54:41.650
have a lot of credibility.

00:54:45.100 --> 00:54:47.430
In other words, in addition to
writing the peer reviewed

00:54:47.430 --> 00:54:51.440
paper, write the white paper,
write the public article.

00:54:51.440 --> 00:54:54.810
And the problem is, at least
academic scientists are not

00:54:54.810 --> 00:54:56.120
rewarded for this.

00:54:56.120 --> 00:54:58.050
It's almost looked down on.

00:54:58.050 --> 00:55:00.420
But what I think, in the old
days in academia it was

00:55:00.420 --> 00:55:02.200
considered bad form
to make money, and

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:03.540
bad from to do policy.

00:55:03.540 --> 00:55:08.410
Nowadays, making money is great,
and I think we have to

00:55:08.410 --> 00:55:11.460
make it so the doing policy is
great too, that there's a

00:55:11.460 --> 00:55:14.560
reward system for taking your
science and using it in the

00:55:14.560 --> 00:55:15.790
public interest.

00:55:15.790 --> 00:55:19.260
Because scientists are paid by
the public, and I think they

00:55:19.260 --> 00:55:23.570
have a responsibility to take
their information and bring it

00:55:23.570 --> 00:55:27.550
to the decision makers, and it
is a huge vacuum, and very

00:55:27.550 --> 00:55:28.800
effective when people do.

00:55:31.600 --> 00:55:32.850
So, other questions.

00:55:37.232 --> 00:55:37.720
Yes.

