00:56:28.860 --> 00:56:31.760
AUDIENCE: About a month ago, I
read a few places, including

00:56:31.760 --> 00:56:34.650
your newsletter, about
brominated vegetable oil

00:56:34.650 --> 00:56:37.410
showing up in Gatorade and a
few other sodas, and I was

00:56:37.410 --> 00:56:41.260
wondering what should we be
avoiding, and also what's

00:56:41.260 --> 00:56:44.300
being done since then to try
and get those removed?

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:45.430
ARLENE BLUM: Yeah, I'm glad
you brought that up.

00:56:45.430 --> 00:56:47.460
That is one of the dumbest
ideas around.

00:56:47.460 --> 00:56:52.700
Back in the '70s, Europe and
Japan all banned brominated--

00:56:52.700 --> 00:56:55.630
we're like the Wild West in
terms of regulation of

00:56:55.630 --> 00:56:57.920
chemicals, sadly enough.

00:56:57.920 --> 00:57:02.240
Anyway, so brominated vegetable
oils are used--

00:57:02.240 --> 00:57:03.380
but it's very specific--

00:57:03.380 --> 00:57:08.120
in certain orange sodas, like
orange Fanta, Mountain Dew,

00:57:08.120 --> 00:57:10.170
certain kinds of Gatorade.

00:57:10.170 --> 00:57:11.180
Just look on the label.

00:57:11.180 --> 00:57:13.960
It'll say brominated vegetable
oils, and they are

00:57:13.960 --> 00:57:20.930
metabolized, stored in our fat,
and I actually was like a

00:57:20.930 --> 00:57:24.570
referee for a paper from Germany
on how bad they are,

00:57:24.570 --> 00:57:27.890
calculating that if a kid lived
on orange Fanta they'd

00:57:27.890 --> 00:57:32.770
get a pretty high dose, and we
can't seem to regulate it.

00:57:32.770 --> 00:57:35.840
We do not have a will to
regulate chemicals, and it's

00:57:35.840 --> 00:57:40.300
really sad, because prevention
is the old thing, but

00:57:40.300 --> 00:57:44.070
prevention is so much cheaper.

00:57:44.070 --> 00:57:46.840
There's a limited number of
really bad chemicals in our

00:57:46.840 --> 00:57:50.070
homes that end up in our bodies,
and they are causing a

00:57:50.070 --> 00:57:53.750
lot of our cancer, infertility,
neurological

00:57:53.750 --> 00:57:56.430
problems, and I feel like we
know what they are, and they

00:57:56.430 --> 00:57:57.320
could be regulated.

00:57:57.320 --> 00:58:03.460
And I think that's an example of
a thing that we don't need.

00:58:03.460 --> 00:58:06.470
It makes it look like the
orange Fanta has fruit

00:58:06.470 --> 00:58:07.120
floating in it.

00:58:07.120 --> 00:58:09.090
It's kind of a density thing
they put in brominated

00:58:09.090 --> 00:58:11.120
vegetable oils.

00:58:11.120 --> 00:58:13.600
So I actually sent out a press
release about that about a

00:58:13.600 --> 00:58:16.490
year ago, and it got some media
attention, but it's

00:58:16.490 --> 00:58:20.050
nobody's business to regulate
it, I guess.

00:58:20.050 --> 00:58:24.320
So you read my newsletter, but
I think if people knew that,

00:58:24.320 --> 00:58:25.850
orange Fanta would
find something.

00:58:25.850 --> 00:58:28.230
In Germany, they have orange
Fanta without brominated

00:58:28.230 --> 00:58:32.240
vegetable oil, so that's the
kind of perfect example of

00:58:32.240 --> 00:58:35.300
something that if we have
information we can solve, and

00:58:35.300 --> 00:58:37.870
where scientists can share
that information.

00:58:37.870 --> 00:58:42.100
I have to say, I reviewed the
paper, gave it high scores,

00:58:42.100 --> 00:58:44.050
and it was not published because
it was not novel

00:58:44.050 --> 00:58:49.880
enough, so how science measures
things is not--

00:58:49.880 --> 00:58:51.780
the people measuring it aren't
measuring it in terms of

00:58:51.780 --> 00:58:53.710
public health.

00:58:53.710 --> 00:58:57.560
The analytic techniques probably
weren't novel enough,

00:58:57.560 --> 00:59:00.830
so somehow there's got to be
some points in paper review

00:59:00.830 --> 00:59:05.240
and in funding for things that
impact public health, and I'm

00:59:05.240 --> 00:59:06.660
afraid there isn't yet.

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:09.320
I guess last question.

00:59:09.320 --> 00:59:17.070
AUDIENCE: I was wondering, is
there an easy, cheap tool that

00:59:17.070 --> 00:59:18.730
anybody can put--

00:59:18.730 --> 00:59:20.390
I understand for different
class of chemicals it's a

00:59:20.390 --> 00:59:22.850
different things-- but that
anybody can put some kind of a

00:59:22.850 --> 00:59:26.660
chemical, or the dust in their
homes, and easily measure

00:59:26.660 --> 00:59:28.120
levels of certain toxins?

00:59:28.120 --> 00:59:29.930
ARLENE BLUM: That
would be great.

00:59:29.930 --> 00:59:31.790
Maybe someone could
develop that.

00:59:31.790 --> 00:59:35.480
But when we did our
studies of--

00:59:35.480 --> 00:59:38.410
we just did a study of what's
in America's couches--

00:59:38.410 --> 00:59:41.100
we were using GC Mass
Spec, which is very

00:59:41.100 --> 00:59:42.095
expensive and difficult.

00:59:42.095 --> 00:59:45.480
No, there aren't, and people
want to know what's in their

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:49.930
couch, and I say, if you live in
California, you don't need

00:59:49.930 --> 00:59:50.910
to bother measuring it.

00:59:50.910 --> 00:59:55.010
But it's expensive, so there's
no easy way, and the other

00:59:55.010 --> 00:59:57.070
part is we don't really
have labeling.

00:59:57.070 --> 00:59:59.770
There's no requirement, and
that's a very simple thing,

00:59:59.770 --> 01:00:02.190
